`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"That question is the foundation of the system I, Jenson Searle, have been building -- a system where saving and loading aren't external tools for player convenience, but laws of physics. In this system, the timeline isn't a straight line. It's a web woven out of your revisions. Each save stitches a new thread into that fabric."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:n.jsx(e.code,{children:"A single thread extends from the final letter. Camera zooms in along the thread, letting the title drift out of frame."})}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"To understand why this matters, we need to look underneath."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:n.jsx(e.code,{children:"Three node-clusters appear along the growing thread."})}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"Most save systems flatten time. They take the entire world -- the player, the state of quests, variables scattered across the map --"}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:n.jsx(e.code,{children:"A player character, a quest log, and bits of the environment appear, shrinking until they're absorbed into the final node."})}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"-- and serialize it into a snapshot. When you load, that snapshot overwrites the present. It's efficient, reliable, perfectly usable for most games... and a total amnesia event for the world."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:n.jsx(e.code,{children:"The two earlier nodes fade out cleanly."})}),`
